# Command Syntax
## Basics
``The command syntax is based off of the RPN syntax in UNIX program `dc```
## Commands
There are 6 main commands, 5 of which relate to the motors, and the last of which is just important flags and direct control over the stack.
``The main commands are `s`, `p`, `t`, `r`, `d`, and `f`.``
``All of these commands will use another letter to determine what they actually do, for all of the commands other than `f`, this means controlling the motors.``
### Speed control
```s` sets the speed of a specific motors, the valid motors for this are `l` (the left motor), `r` (the right motor), and `c` (the central motor). Calling `s` will pop a value off of the stack and set it as the speed at which the specified motor will run``
### Relative position control
```p` sets the number of degrees a specified motor will run for, valid motors are the same as for the `s` command. Also pops a value off of the stack``
### Time control
```t` sets the number of milliseconds that a specified motor will run for, otherwise same as `s` and `p`.
### Polarity control
```d` sets the polarity of a specified motor, value is given as index number that is defiend in `ev3_tacho.h`, otherwise same as `s`.``
### Commands control
```r` sets the command for the motor, value is given as index number that is defined in `ev3_tacho.h`, only difference in the motors that this can control is that the motor letter `d` will run the motors `l` and `r` at the same time. Otherwise same motors as other control commands```
### Special flags & commands
```f` has special controls in it that can be used for different things.
`fs` will add a timed break in the instructions, this value is given in microseconds.
`fr` will pop and return a value directly from the stack, does nothing else.
`fl` will return the decimal value 2, for setting flag that it will run the follower function.
`fe` will return the decimal value 0, for exiting any loops that were started with `fl`.```
## Eample Command
`1000 sl 720 pl 3 rl`
``This will set the speed of motor `l` to 1000, set the relative position of motor `l` to 720 degrees, and then sends the command to run to the specified relative position of motor `l`.  ``
